context: The development of skyscrapers over 300 feet (91 m) in San Diego is attributed to the construction of the <a0_0><b5_0>El Cortez Hotel<b5_0/><a0_0/> in 1927, the tallest building in the city from 1927 to 1963. As time went on multiple buildings claimed the title of San Diego's tallest skyscraper, including the <a4_0><b9_0>Union Bank of California Building<b9_0/><a4_0/> and Symphony Towers. Currently the tallest building in San Diego is One America Plaza, standing <a1_0><b6_0>500 feet<b6_0/><a1_0/> (150 m) tall, which was completed in 1991. The downtown skyline contains no super-talls, as a regulation put in place by the <a3_0><b8_0>Federal Aviation Administration<b8_0/><a3_0/> in the 1970s set a 500 feet (152 m) limit on the height of buildings due to the proximity of <a2_0><b7_0>San Diego International Airport<b7_0/><a2_0/>. An iconic description of the skyline includes its skyscrapers being compared to the tools of a toolbox.
